A special fund was established in Vietnam for victims of Agent Orange, a toxic defoliant used during the Vietnam War.
The fund, managed by the Red Cross, will provide loans to those affected by the chemical.
Recent studies show dioxin levels are dropping, but the toxic effects are still impacting multiple generations.
A court ruling in 1989 voided VA benefit decisions based on outdated information about Agent Orange.
The Institute of Medicine's report maintains a list of diseases linked to herbicide exposure, but no new evidence has emerged.
Efforts continue to support victims and research the long-term health effects of Agent Orange.
